abstract = {Investigated the validity of self-assessment against ratings by examiners and by peers in highly competitive selection situations. 230 engineers (aged 22–28 yrs) applying for jobs and 187 undergraduates applying for admission to a professional school were assigned to groups of 8–22 Ss in order to participate in a group task and group discussion. Ss then ranked the members of their group. Three examiners also rated Ss. Results show that (a) a strong tendency to overestimation dominated self-appraisal; (b) self-assessment was unpredictable compared to examiners' and peers' assessments, though the 2 criteria were highly correlated; and (c) the moderating effect of the psychological and biographical factors had little effect on the self-assessment of older and more qualified Ss. However, SES, academic achievement, favorable family background, good schooling, and urban background had positive moderating effects on the quality of self-reporting of younger and less qualified Ss. (27 ref) (PsycINFO Database Record (c) 2012 APA, all rights reserved)},
